  "text": "## Health Check Endpoint Implementation Comparison\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/healthz` - liveness/general health\n- `/livez` - liveness (subset of readiness checks)\n- `/readyz` - readiness (when ready to serve traffic)\n\n**Implementation** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go`):\nKubernetes has a comprehensive health check framework with pluggable health checkers. The endpoints are registered via `InstallHandler()`, `InstallLivezHandler()`, and `InstallReadyzHandler()` functions in the healthz package. Each endpoint supports multiple health checks that can be selectively excluded via query parameters (e.g., `/healthz?exclude=etcd`).\n\n**Checks Performed:**\n1. **Ping check** - Basic liveness (always passes)\n2. **Log check** - Verifies logging is not blocked\n3. **Informer sync check** - Readyz only, ensures all Kubernetes informers have synced\n4. **Shutdown check** - Detects graceful shutdown state\n5. **etcd health checks** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/options/etcd.go`):\n   - etcd-healthiness: Tests basic etcd connectivity\n   - etcd-readiness: Tests if etcd is ready for API operations\n   - Supports multiple etcd server configurations with per-server health checks\n6. **API service availability checks** - Custom checks for API service discovery\n7. **Post-start hook checks** - Tracks completion of post-start initialization hooks\n\n**Key Features:**\n- Grouped health checks (e.g., etcd checks are grouped under \"etcd\" group for bulk exclusion)\n- Individual endpoint access: `/readyz/ping`, `/readyz/etcd-readiness`, etc.\n- Verbose output: `/readyz?verbose=1` shows individual check results\n- Prometheus SLI integration for observability\n\n---\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/-/healthy` - Health check (always returns 200 OK)\n- `/-/ready` - Readiness check (depends on server state)\n\n**Implementation** (`web/web.go`):\nPrometheus uses a simple state-machine based health model. The web Handler maintains a `ready` field using atomic operations with three states: `NotReady`, `Ready`, and `Stopping`. The `/-/healthy` endpoint always responds with 200 OK to indicate the HTTP server is running. The `/-/ready` endpoint uses the `testReady()` method (aliased as `readyf` when registering routes) to check the current ready state.\n\n**Checks Performed:**\n1. **HTTP server liveness** - `/-/healthy` always returns 200 OK with message \"{AppName} is Healthy\"\n2. **TSDB readiness** - `/-/ready` checks the internal ready status:\n   - Returns 200 OK if `Ready`\n   - Returns 503 Service Unavailable with appropriate state if `NotReady` or `Stopping`\n   - Sets `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true` header during graceful shutdown\n   - Sets `X-Prometheus-Stopping: false` during normal NotReady state\n\n**State Transitions:**\n- Server starts in `NotReady` state\n- Transitions to `Ready` when TSDB and storage are initialized\n- Transitions to `Stopping` when shutdown signal is received\n\n**Configuration:**\nThe ready status is managed via `SetReady()` method, allowing the main Prometheus application to coordinate readiness with storage initialization. The `testReady()` handler wraps HTTP handlers to enforce the readiness check.\n\n---\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/healthz` - Simple health check (always returns 200 OK)\n- `/api/health` - Comprehensive health check with database status\n- `/readyz` - Proxied to Kubernetes-compatible endpoint via apiserver service\n\n**Implementation:**\n\n**Simple Health (`pkg/api/http_server.go` - `healthzHandler`):**\nThe `/healthz` endpoint simply returns HTTP 200 with message \"Ok\" if the web server is running. No dependencies are checked; it's a pure liveness indicator.\n\n**Comprehensive Health (`pkg/api/http_server.go` - `apiHealthHandler`):**\nThe `/api/health` endpoint checks database connectivity and returns:\n- HTTP 200 with database status \"ok\" if healthy\n- HTTP 503 (Service Unavailable) with database status \"failing\" if database is inaccessible\n- Response includes version, commit, and enterprise commit information (when not anonymized)\n\n**Database Health Check** (`pkg/api/health.go` - `databaseHealthy()`):\n1. Checks cache for recent health status (5-second TTL)\n2. Executes `SELECT 1` query via `SQLStore.WithDbSession()` to verify database connectivity\n3. Caches result for 5 seconds to reduce database load\n4. Returns boolean indicating database health\n\n**Kubernetes API Server Integration:**\nGrafana's Kubernetes API server implementation proxies `/readyz` and `/healthz` endpoints through the generic apiserver service, allowing Kubernetes-native health check conventions to be applied to Grafana's integrated API server.\n\n---\n\n## Key Differences Summary\n\n| Aspect | Kubernetes | Prometheus | Grafana |\n|--------|-----------|------------|----------|\n| **Liveness Check** | `/healthz` with pluggable checks | `/-/healthy` (always 200) | `/healthz` (always 200) |\n| **Readiness Check** | `/readyz` with detailed checks | `/-/ready` (state-based) | `/api/health` (DB-dependent) |\n| **Dependencies Checked** | etcd, informers, post-start hooks, API services | TSDB/storage state | Database connectivity |\n| **Failure Response** | HTTP 500 with detailed failure reasons | HTTP 503 with state header | HTTP 503 with DB status |\n| **Check Framework** | Modular pluggable system | Simple state machine | Simple DB query test |\n| **Verbose Mode** | Yes (`?verbose=1`) | No | No |\n| **Header Signaling** | HTTP status only | `X-Prometheus-Stopping` header | HTTP status only |\n"

